Is there a more magical place on earth than Nahanni National Park Reserve? We might be biased, but we don’t think so! Nahanni National Park Reserve is considered a paradise for those adventurers who pursue remote wilderness. Alpinists are drawn to the Cirque of Unclimbables, paddlers explore the heart of the reserve and mountaineers trek, compass in hand, across range, meadow and karst. Interpreters located within the park convey the Dene culture to the curious. Want to learn more?  http://www.pc.gc.ca/en/pn-np/nt/nahanni

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Stay tuned!

caption_original:
Effective immediately, vessels travelling in the western Gulf of St. Lawrence are mandated to reduce their speed to a maximum of 10 knots. The Government of Canada implemented the temporary mandatory slow-down for vessels longer than 20 metres in an effort to minimize risks to right whales in the area.

 
Following the recent whale deaths in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, we are making every effort possible to prevent further incidents and continue to work on the recovery of the species. We are awaiting results from the necropsies, and we have closed snow crab fishing to prevent entanglements.  Other fixed gear fisheries such as rock and toad crab fisheries have either been restricted to fish in shallow water or have had a delayed opening. For more information on our actions to date: http://ow.ly/n5qc30el2Kw

Transport and Infrastructure in Canada
caption_cleaned: Effective immediately, vessels travelling in the western Gulf of St. Lawrence are mandated to reduce their speed to a maximum of knots. The Government of Canada implemented the temporary mandatory slow-down for vessels longer than metres in an effort to minimize risks to right whales in the area. Following the recent whale deaths in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, we are making every effort possible to prevent further incidents and continue to work on the recovery of the species. We are awaiting results from the necropsies, and we have closed snow crab fishing to prevent entanglements. Other fixed gear fisheries such as rock and toad crab fisheries have either been restricted to fish in shallow water or have had a delayed opening. For more information on our actions to date: Transport and Infrastructure in Canada

caption_original:
On Tuesday August 29 the Canadian Coast Guard successfully located four hikers who had lost their way along the Lighthouse Trail at Killarney. The Ontario Provincial Police requested assistance via the Joint Rescue Coordination Centre in Trenton Ontario.

The Coast Guard's inshore rescue boat crew stationed at Britt was tasked to search for 3 females, one male and their dog. 

The Coast Guard brought the group aboard their fast rescue craft and transported them back to Killarney. All were in good condition.

Photo caption: From left to right Stephen Pitman, Mollie King, and Keith Pettinger of the Canadian Coast Guard Inshore Rescue Boat station at Britt. The crew assisted four hikers and their dog at Tar Vat Bay Tuesday August 29 2017

Our crew aboard CCGS Constable Carrière, one of our mid-shore patrol vessels that provides maritime security on the Great Lakes, is honoured to attend the Grand Haven Coast Guard Festival in western Michigan. Each year, this festival in Grand Haven, which is known as Coast Guard City USA, attracts hundreds of thousands of visitors, and honours those who have sacrificed their lives in the service of their country. The two Coast Guards deliver a multitude of maritime services including Search and Rescue, Environmental Response, Icebreaking, Marine Communications and Traffic Services, Aids to Navigation, Maritime Security and Waterways Management.
Photos: Petty Officer 2nd Class Lauren Steenson, U.S. Coast Guard

caption_original:
We are taking action on the recovery, protection and conservation of the endangered North Atlantic Right Whale. The deaths of the whales in the Gulf of St. Lawrence this summer is an unprecedented situation.  
 
We are conducting necropsies on the deceased whales with partners to learn the cause of death and determine next steps. We closed some snow crab fisheries early and other fixed gear fisheries have either been restricted or have been delayed. We have notified fishermen to stay on high alert and report any sightings. We are regularly conducting surveillance flights to monitor for whales. The Canadian Coast Guard is asking shipping vessels entering our waters to decrease their speed until further notice.  

Learn more about what we are doing to protect the North Atlantic Right whales: http://ow.ly/MVlC30e8Nu4

Our Fishery Officers are actively monitoring and enforcing all fishing activity using a variety of methods, including aerial, ocean, river, on-the-ground, night and undercover patrols. caption_original: Weighing one and a half tonnes, the Atlantic walrus may look clumsy and slow-moving on land. But in the water, they are smooth and graceful swimmers. They have poor vision but they are still excellent at hunting, using their sensitive whiskers to detect prey and strong suction to swallow them. The Atlantic walrus prefers cold waters and there may still be up to several thousand walruses in Canadian waters. http://ow.ly/UlWs30eJiJt

caption_original: Many of the leatherback sea turtles seen in our waters nest in Trinidad and Tobago. Every year, our Sea Turtle Biologist Mike James travels there to work with local conservation groups to collect data from nesting leatherback sea turtles. His work enables remote detecting of turtles on the beach so research can be done throughout the nesting season. Last week, his Trinidad and Tobago colleagues joined him in Halifax to discuss how they can further this collaboration and observe research activities underway off Nova Scotia.

caption_original: Did you know that the establishment of marine protected areas is one of the measures taken by the Government of Canada to protect and preserve our oceans? Marine protected areas are geographically delimited marine zones that are managed for the purpose of conserving and protecting: marine species – including endangered species – and their populations; diversity of the ecosystems on which these species depend; representative marine environments; as well as unique locations such as submarine canyons and hydrothermal vents. They can allow certain present and future activities by taking account of their impacts on protected ecological characteristics. To better understand what marine protected areas are: http://ow.ly/NInc30esAzg

caption_original:
Located in the eastern Gaspé Peninsula in Quebec, the American Bank was selected in 2011 as a potential site for a new Marine Protected Area. In-depth knowledge of the site is an essential prerequisite for creating a Marine Protected Area. We know the site has many assets: diversity of its habitats; presence of many commercially valuable species and species at risk; as well as significant potential as a feeding ground for various species of fish and marine mammals. http://ow.ly/dADN30eoIQY 

The establishment of the American Bank as a Marine Protected Area should promote the productivity and diversity of commercially fished species as well as the recovery of species at risk.
caption_cleaned: Located in the eastern Gaspé Peninsula in Quebec, the American Bank was selected in as a potential site for a new Marine Protected Area. In-depth knowledge of the site is an essential prerequisite for creating a Marine Protected Area. We know the site has many assets: diversity of its habitats; presence of many commercially valuable species and species at risk; as well as significant potential as a feeding ground for various species of fish and marine mammals. The establishment of the American Bank as a Marine Protected Area should promote the productivity and diversity of commercially fished species as well as the recovery of species at risk.

caption_original: Student research assistants Nicolas Piette-Lauziere and Zoik Brault are in the field at the edge of Cape Breton Highlands National Park. They are proudly displaying their commemorative t-shirts! Over the last month, Nicolas and Zoik have been mapping a fault zone on Cape Breton Island that separates rocks with different geological histories on either side. By studying the fault zone in the field, and collecting samples to study in the lab, Nicolas hopes to discover when and why it formed, and how it may have created a pathway for magma deep in the Earth’s crust to rise and form granite.

Be wary of unsolicited emails or text messages asking you to call a number to get more information about a service or promotion.

Typically, 900 and 976 numbers are pay-per-call services, which means you’re paying for calls originating from or charged to your telephone, no matter who made the calls or accepted the charges. 

You can request a call-blocking feature from your telephone company. Learn more: http://ow.ly/gJus30ejL0b

For example, the age at which you apply for the Canada Pension Plan or Quebec Pension Plan can affect how much you get.

caption_original: Shark sightings and accidental interactions are common in Newfoundland and Labrador waters and the public plays a vital role in shark research. If you see a shark, dead or alive, take a photo. Note the date and location and send it to Carolyn.Miri@dfo-mpo.gc.ca. But do it safely. No shark selfies! Don’t bring the shark aboard your boat. caption_original:
On July 31, Adam Erland, Regional Supervisor Maritime Search and Rescue for Joint Rescue Coordination Centre Halifax, joined other VIPs for a tour of the United States Coast Guard Cutter EAGLE while it was in port for the annual Tall Ships Festival in Halifax, Nova Scotia. The delegation included USCGC EAGLE Captain Matthew T. Meilstrup and his Executive Officer, the U.S. Consulate General for Atlantic Canada Steven S. Giegerich, President and CEO of the Halifax Port Authority Karen Oldfield, City of Halifax Mayor Mike Savage, and representatives from the Halifax Airport Commission and the Halifax Chamber of Commerce.   

The Canadian Coast Guard regularly works with its American counterparts on exercises and training opportunities in support of safety of mariners and the marine environment.

The delegation included USCGC EAGLE Captain Matthew T. Meilstrup and his Executive Officer, the U.S. Consulate General for Atlantic Canada Steven S. Giegerich, President and CEO of the Halifax Port Authority Karen Oldfield, City of Halifax Mayor Mike Savage, and representatives from the Halifax Airport Commission and the Halifax Chamber of Commerce. The Canadian Coast Guard regularly works with its American counterparts on exercises and training opportunities in support of safety of mariners and the marine environment.

Do you live in Atlantic Canada? What do you love most about it? Is it:

- Coastal living? 
- Easy access to nature and wildlife at our many beaches, forests, and parks?
- Hiking through rugged and pristine landscapes?
- Friendly people and a close-knit community? 

If you said yes to one or more of these activities you might want to join us in the Atlantic Canada Shorebird Survey (ACSS)!   Volunteer bird watchers help us by gathering vital information that helps the Canadian Wildlife Service (CWS) to better understand the migratory birds that stop-over along our shores on the East Coast. http://ow.ly/Uqin30eBrqg

For beluga whales, the St. Lawrence Estuary is a critical living environment. This is where they are born, live, eat, and socialize. The St. Lawrence belugas are endangered. caption_original:
Ice delays have the science team working on experimental approaches to tracking and understanding narwhal and their ecosystem in Tremblay Sound, Nunavut. We’re finding ways to turn tracking studies into community-based research projects. Summer gathering areas like Tremblay Sound are well-known to Inuit, and Inuit researchers are excited by long-term research opportunities.

This week, the team has been working to install a series of Very High Frequency receiving stations in Tremblay Sound. These stations will allow us to follow tagged narwhals and better understand their behaviour. 

Photos: © Troy Neale/Vancouver Aquarium

The Agency's enforcement powers are set out in legislation and regulation. These enforcement powers include:

• ensuring the aircraft are insured and authorized under licence by Transport Canada,
• verification of flight records, tickets, invoices and other financial records,
• reviewing airline tariffs to ensure they comply with the licence and the law,
• ensure that companies have training programs in place to train employees to help persons with disabilities,
• ensure that advertisers of air fares comply with all-inclusive air price advertising regulations.

For more information about the scope and limits to our enforcement activities, see http://ow.ly/NaYZ30ejT8b

Canadians want to live in clean and healthy communities. The Government of Canada is providing funding to deal with air pollution, help create clean growth, and support clean energy. Let’s grow in a way that doesn’t harm our environment. 

The Government of Canada is working to meet its federal sustainable development goals on clean energy, clean growth, and safe and healthy communities. They support the 2030 agenda’s “Good Health and Well-Being” , “Affordable and Clean Energy”, “Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure”, and “Responsible Consumption and Production” goals.

The update to the Federal Sustainable Development Strategy is available here: http://ow.ly/BxK030eCW17 It lets you know what actions are being taken. #FSDS

Check out the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development goals: http://ow.ly/Dx4t30eCW2X

caption_original:
Last week was the first deadline to apply for funding through the Environmental Damages Fund (EDF). There’s still more available! If you’re in Northern Québec or Labrador regions, EDF still has $3.45M in funding available until October 31.

A Québec company was ordered to pay $7.5M after pleading guilty to 45 charges under the Fisheries Act. This is the largest penalty ever given for an environmental infraction. Environment and Climate Change Canada puts a lot of consideration into where the funds go. Of that $7.5M, $6.83 was directed to EDF and today $3.45 is available to fund projects that will benefit the affected area.

For more information about this Fund and to find out if your project qualifies for funding, click here: http://ow.ly/Cbb130e4RtF

caption_original:

caption_original:
#TravelTips > Know Your Carrier's Limits

Each carrier sets out its own limits for carry-on and checked baggage. Carriers also set time limits for reporting and filing complaints about lost, damaged or delayed baggage. Check your carrier's tariff for its baggage rules and allowances.

 #FlySmart > Top 10 Tips > http://ow.ly/uy2l3061cit
caption_cleaned: > Know Your Carrier's Limits Each carrier sets out its own limits for carry-on and checked baggage. Carriers also set time limits for reporting and filing complaints about lost, damaged or delayed baggage. Check your carrier's tariff for its baggage rules and allowances. > Top Tips >

caption_original:
#TravelTips > Call Ahead

From carrying sports equipment and musical instruments, to dietary restrictions, medical conditions and disability-related needs, most carriers require from 48 to 72 hours notice to accommodate special requests.

 #FlySmart > Top 10 Tips > http://ow.ly/uy2l3061cit
caption_cleaned: > Call Ahead From carrying sports equipment and musical instruments, to dietary restrictions, medical conditions and disability-related needs, most carriers require from to hours notice to accommodate special requests. > Top Tips >

caption_original:
#TravelTips > Pack Smart

Include your contact information and your destination contact information inside each piece of baggage. Always carry essential and valuable items with you on board: your passport, identification and return tickets; medicines and medical devices; money, jewelry and electronic equipment; and, essential overnight items.

 #FlySmart > Top 10 Tips > http://ow.ly/uy2l3061cit
